<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-11-24T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-11-24T14:00:00-05:00" n="230" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d230">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">860h.00/34: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Special Representative</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">House</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                                </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-11-24T19:00:00+00:00">November 24, 1918—7 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received November 24—5:36 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>163. Referring to 106 [<hi rend="italic">120?</hi>]<note n="19a" xml:id="d230fn19a">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_297">p.
                                297</ref>.</note> and 145.<note n="20" xml:id="d230fn20">
                                <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                            </note> I have received the following reply from the French Foreign
                            Office: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“I have the honor to inform you that the French Government is
                                    favorable to the presence, in regions of the former Austrian
                                    Hungarian Monarchy where the populations are partly Italian and
                                    partly Jugo-Slav, of troops belonging to the Allied countries
                                    who would not find themselves drawn into conflicts of
                                    nationality. The French Government can, therefore, only regard
                                    with pleasure the despatch of American troops to the territories
                                    where they will find French detachments beside them.”</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Edward House</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>